Acumatica ERP Construction Edition provides multiple construction reports that can be provided to customers. ==Learning Objectives== In this chapter, you will learn how to do the following:[anchor|#_66238f4e-cd01-4326-b4b2-333852c8c4cf] *Printand send substantiated billing reports and understand which information is included in them *Print and send work-in-progress reports and understand which information is included in them *Print and send American Institute of Architects (AIA) reports and understand which information is included in them *Print and send bonding reports and understand which information is included in them *Review the project life cycle and performance with the help of described reports
==Substantiated Billing Report== In the construction industry, when contractors bill their customers, the customers may want to see proof of the costs. In this case, contractors need to provide supporting documentation along with the customer statement or invoice. Acumatica ERP Construction Editionincludes the following substantiated billing reports that you can use to retrieve costs for a specific billing period:[anchor|#ul_u4j_qxg_qmb] *[HelpRoot_Construction\PM_65_00_00|Substantiated Billing] ([~/?ScreenId=PM650000|PM650000]) *:The substantiated billing report provides a list of costs for the specified period with all transactions related to payable invoices, labor, and other project expenses grouped by the cost codes. *[HelpRoot_Construction\PM_65_00_50|Substantiated Billing - Consolidated] ([~/?ScreenId=PM650050|PM650050]) *:In addition to the list of costs and transactions of a project for the specified period, the generated report includes all scanned or uploaded images of the PNG, JPG, JPEG, BMP, GIF, TIFF or TIF format attached to the corresponding cost records as separate pages. Also, the generated report file includes hyperlinks to the attached files that could not be included directly in the PDF file (such as, for example, encrypted PDF files). You can see these files by clicking the hyperlink and entering guest credentials into the Acumatica ERP sign-in page.
==WIP Report== WIP (work-in-progress or work-in-process) is designed to track the progress of active jobs, as well as their financial performance. In addition to looking at the percentage of completion and the cost to complete, it also determines whether a job is overbilled or underbilled relative to its progress. When using the percentage-of-completion method for revenue recognition, companies include a WIP schedule with their financial statements. {br}
Acumatica ERP Construction Edition supports several versions of WIP reporting, providing necessary information, and with the recent inclusion of a bonding report, surety companies have visibility into a business’s performance.[anchor|#section_skv_pn4_qmb] ==AIA Report== The common construction billing format is known as AIA progress billing, named after the American Institute of Architects that produces its official forms. As a type of progress billing, AIA billing invoices (which are provided as AIA reports in Acumatica ERP Construction Edition) the customer based on the percentage of work completed for that billing period. For detailed description of the information included to AIA reports, see [HelpRoot_Construction\Construction_Reports_AIA|Construction Reports: AIA Reports]. ==Bonding Report== By using the [HelpRoot_Construction\PM_65_05_00|Construction Bonding Report], you can create a report of work in progress for projects for a selected date range. This report can be used by management as well as external entities, such as bonding companies, to determine the financial health of projects. The report gives a bigger snapshot of all the projects in the system and provides management confidence. You could analyze how much is actually billed for the project compared to the percentage of the project completion.{br}
The [HelpRoot_Construction\PM_65_05_00|Construction Bonding Report] ([~/?ScreenId=PM650500|PM650500])includes the following columns: Earned Revenue, Billed to Date, Unbilled Contract Amounts, as well as Cost Incurred to Date, Calculated Cost at Completion, Current Period Costs/Billings, as well as the prior year&rsquo;s Billings and Costs.

The following sections describe the structure of the AIA report and the available report variations. Also, the sections provide information on and how you can reflect historic retainage and change order release, and how you can print the AIA report for billing the retainage solely.[anchor|#section_j3j_qpv_qmb] ==AIA Report Structure== The AIA report consists of a signed summary sheet (AIA Document G702™–1992, Application and Certificate for Payment), followed by a schedule of values (G703™–1992, Continuation Sheet) that details the project tasks that has been completed and billed to date. Together, these documents are considered an application for payment, because the recipient will have a chance to review the schedule of values and either accept or dispute the billed amount. If they disagree, they will send back redlines so that the contractor can revise and resubmit the AIA billing application. The prepared document that includes both application sheet (G702) and continuation sheet (G703) is called AIA report{br}
In AIA report, application sheet along with continuation sheet provide convenient and complete forms on which the contractor can apply for payment and the architect can certify that payment is due. The application require the contractor to show the status of the contract sum to date, including the total amount of the work completed and stored to date, the amount of retainage (if any), the total of previous payments, a summary of change orders, and the amount of current payment requested. The continuation sheet breaks the contract sum into portions of the work in accordance with a schedule of values prepared by the contractor as required by the general conditions. ((({S:Warn}The AIA report does not publish a standard schedule of values form. AIA report serves as both the contractor’s application and the architect’s certification. Using AIA report helps to expedite payment and reduces the possibility of errors. If the application is properly completed and acceptable to the architect, the architect’s signature certifies to the owner that a payment in the amount indicated is due to the contractor. The form also allows the architect to certify an amount different than the amount applied for, with explanation provided by the architect. )))[anchor|#section_tkv_pn4_qmb] ==Configuring AIA Report Parameters for a Project== Based on project requirements, for a particular project, you define the format in which the AIA report will be prepared. To prepare the printable version of the AIA report, you select the line with the needed pro forma invoice in the table on the '''Invoices''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PM_30_10_00|Projects] ([~/?ScreenId=PM301000|PM301000]) form, and click '''AIA Report''' on the table toolbar; you can instead open the pro forma invoice on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PM_30_70_00|Pro Forma Invoices] ([~/?ScreenId=PM307000|PM307000]) form and click the '''AIA Report''' button on the form toolbar.{br}
By default, a newly created project has the '''AIA Level''' setting set to ''Summary'' and the '''Show Quantity in AIA Report''' check box cleared. When you create an AIA report for such a project, the standard AIA report ([HelpRoot_Construction\PM_64_40_00|AIA Report]'' ([~/?ScreenId=PM644000|PM644000])'') with continuation sheet lines grouped by project tasks is prepared.{br}
If you need to include quantities to the lines of the continuation sheet of the AIA report prepared for a project, in the settings of the project on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PM_30_10_00|Projects] form, select the '''Show Quantity in AIA Report''' check box, so that the system will create the [HelpRoot_Construction\PM_64_45_00|AIA Report with Quantity]'' ([~/?ScreenId=PM644500|PM644500])'' report. To list the continuation sheet lines without grouping by project tasks (that is, as they are presented in the corresponding pro forma invoice), select ''Detail'' in the '''AIA Level''' box.[anchor|#section_pbt_tqy_rmb] ==Date-Sensitive Data in AIA Reports== AIA reports are date-sensitive, which means that the particular amounts are included or not included to the report based on the report date; this in turn could lead to differences between calculation of amounts in AIA reports and financial calculations in other documents. The date on which the AIA report is prepared affects the following amounts in AIA application sheet:[anchor|#ul_nx1_hry_rmb] *To the '''Net Change by Change Orders''' amount, the system includes only change orders that have the approval date less then the invoice date of the pro forma invoice, for which the AIA report is being prepared. *To the '''Retainage''' amount, the system does not include the retainage that have been released before creation of the pro forma invoice for which the AIA report is being prepared (that is, the invoice date of the retainage invoice is less then the invoice date of the pro forma invoice). *To the '''Less Previous Certificates for Payment''' amount, the system includes the sum of the retainage amount that have been released before the date of the previous application (that is, the invoice date of the retainage invoice is less then or equal to the invoice date of the previous pro forma invoice prepared for the project). *To the '''Current Payment Due''' amount, the system includes the amounts of retainage invoices that have been prepared since the last application (that is, the invoice date of the retainage invoice is greater then the invoice date of the previous pro forma invoice and is less then or equal to the invoice date of the pro forma invoice for which the AIA report is prepared).
The date on which the AIA report is prepared affects the following amounts in AIA continuation sheet:[anchor|#ul_zpr_5ty_rmb] *To the amounts in the '''Change Orders''' and '''Change Qty.''' columns, the system includes only change orders that have the approval date less then the invoice date of the pro forma invoice, for which the AIA report is being prepared. *To the '''Retainage Held''', the system does not include the retainage that have been released before creation of the pro forma invoice for which the AIA report is being prepared (that is, the invoice date of the retainage invoice is less then the invoice date of the pro forma invoice). [anchor|#section_mdp_qp4_qmb] ==AIA Reports for Released Retainage== If the ''Retainage Support'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, you can create AIA report that will include the retainage that has been fully or partially released (depending on the date for which the AIA report is prepared), or all released retainage at the end of the project.{br}
You can prepare an AIA report for released retainage if the following conditions are met:[anchor|#ul_f1c_dq4_qmb] *The retainage in the financial period for which the report is being prepared has been released. *The zero pro forma invoice has been created, and the invoice date of the zero pro forma invoice is the same as or later than the date of the corresponding AR retainage invoice. *:A zero pro forma invoice could be created only if in the billing rule assigned to a project task, the '''Create Lines with Zero Amounts''' check box is selected in the progress billing step on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PM_20_70_00|Billing Rules] ([~/?ScreenId=PM207000|PM207000]) form. You run project billing for a project with a pending invoice amount of zero to prepare a zero pro forma invoice.
If all conditions are met, to prepare the printable version of the AIA report, you select the line with the zero pro forma invoice in the table on the '''Invoices''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PM_30_10_00|Projects] ([~/?ScreenId=PM301000|PM301000]) form, and click '''AIA Report''' on the table toolbar (or open the zero pro forma invoice and click the '''AIA Report''' button on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PM_30_70_00|Pro Forma Invoices] ([~/?ScreenId=PM307000|PM307000]) form). Depending on the date for which the AIA report is prepared, the report will include the retainage that has been fully or partially released in the middle of the project, or all released retainage at the end of the project. In the prepared report, the total retainage amount on the cover sheet of the AIA report is calculated as the sum of the held retainage amounts on the AIA continuation sheet.

